Reconfigurations of space in Partition novels

          Par Sandrine Soukaï

          leadIamge

          This article examines two Indian novels ((Clear Light of Day))
          (1980) by Anita Desai and ((The Shadow Lines)) (1988) by Amitav
          Ghosh along with ((Burnt Shadows)) (2009) by Anglo-Pakistani
          novelist Kamila Shamsie, books written about the Partition of
          India that accompanied independence in 1947. Partition led to
          violence on an enormous scale; the exact number of people who
          were killed has never been ascertained, and estimates vary
          between one and two million. Partition also caused massive (...)

          Lire l'article

